#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:12
msgid "So far our application has a registry that may monitor dozens, if not hundreds, of buckets. While we think our implementation so far is quite good, no software is bug free, and failures are definitely going to happen."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:14
msgid "When things fail, your first reaction may be: \"let's rescue those errors\". But in Elixir we avoid the defensive programming habit of rescuing exceptions. Instead, we say \"let it crash\". If there is a bug that leads our registry to crash, we have nothing to worry about because we are going to set up a supervisor that will start a fresh copy of the registry."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:16
msgid "In this chapter, we are going to learn about supervisors and also about applications. We are going to create not one, but two supervisors, and use them to supervise our processes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:18
msgid "## Our first supervisor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:20
msgid "Creating a supervisor is not much different from creating a GenServer. We are going to define a module named `KV.Supervisor`, which will use the [Supervisor](https://hexdocs.pm/elixir/Supervisor.html) behaviour, inside the `lib/kv/supervisor.ex` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:22
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"defmodule KV.Supervisor do\n"
"  use Supervisor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:26
msgid ""
"  def start_link(opts) do\n"
"    Supervisor.start_link(__MODULE__, :ok, opts)\n"
"  end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:30
msgid ""
"  def init(:ok) do\n"
"    children = [\n"
"      KV.Registry\n"
"    ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:35
msgid ""
"    Supervisor.init(children, strategy: :one_for_one)\n"
"  end\n"
"end\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:40
msgid "Our supervisor has a single child so far: `KV.Registry`. After we define a list of children, we call `Supervisor.init/2`, passing the children and the supervision strategy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:42
msgid "The supervision strategy dictates what happens when one of the children crashes. `:one_for_one` means that if a child dies, it will be the only one restarted. Since we have only one child now, that's all we need. The `Supervisor` behaviour supports many different strategies and we will discuss them in this chapter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:44
msgid "Once the supervisor starts, it will traverse the list of children and it will invoke the `child_spec/1` function on each module. We heard about the `child_spec/1` function in the Agent chapter, when we called `start_supervised(KV.Bucket)` without defining the module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:46
msgid "The `child_spec/1` function returns the child specification which describes how to start the process, if the process is a worker or a supervisor, if the process is temporary, transient or permanent and so on. The `child_spec/1` function is automatically defined when we `use Agent`, `use GenServer`, `use Supervisor`, etc. Let's give it a try in the terminal with `iex -S mix`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:48
msgid ""
"```iex\n"
"iex(1)> KV.Registry.child_spec([])\n"
"%{\n"
"  id: KV.Registry,\n"
"  restart: :permanent,\n"
"  shutdown: 5000,\n"
"  start: {KV.Registry, :start_link, [[]]},\n"
"  type: :worker\n"
"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:59
msgid "We will learn those details as we move forward on this guide. If you would rather peek ahead, check the [Supervisor](https://hexdocs.pm/elixir/Supervisor.html) docs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:61
msgid "After the supervisor retrieves all child specifications, it proceeds to start its children one by one, in the order they were defined, using the information in the `:start` key in the child specification. For our current specification, it will call `KV.Registry.start_link([])`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:63
msgid "So far `start_link/1` has always receive an empty list of options. It is time we change that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:65
msgid "## Naming processes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:67
msgid "While our application will have many buckets, it will only have a single registry. So instead of always passing the registry PID around, we can give the registry a name, and always reference it by its name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:69
msgid "Also, remember buckets were started dynamically based on user input, and that meant we should not use atom names for managing our buckets. But the registry is in the opposite situation, we want to start a single registry, preferrably under a supervisor, when our application boots."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:71
msgid "So let's do that. Let's slightly change our children definition to be a list of tuples instead of a list of atoms:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:73
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"  def init(:ok) do\n"
"    children = [\n"
"      {KV.Registry, name: KV.Registry}\n"
"    ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:79 ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:347
msgid ""
"    Supervisor.init(children, strategy: :one_for_one)\n"
"  end\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:83
msgid "The difference now is that, instead of calling `KV.Registry.start_link([])`, the Supervisor will call `KV.Registry.start_link([name: KV.Registry])`. If you revisit `KV.Registry.start_link/1` implementation, you will remember it simply passes the options to GenServer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:85
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"  def start_link(opts) do\n"
"    GenServer.start_link(__MODULE__, :ok, opts)\n"
"  end\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:91
msgid "which in turn will register the process with the given name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:93
msgid "Let's give this all a try inside `iex -S mix`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:95
msgid ""
"```iex\n"
"iex> KV.Supervisor.start_link([])\n"
"{:ok, #PID<0.66.0>}\n"
"iex> KV.Registry.create(KV.Registry, \"shopping\")\n"
":ok\n"
"iex> KV.Registry.lookup(KV.Registry, \"shopping\")\n"
"{:ok, #PID<0.70.0>}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:104
msgid "When we started the supervisor, the registry was automatically started with the given name, allowing us to create buckets without the need to manually start it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:106
msgid "In practice we rarely start the application supervisor manually. Instead it is started as part of the application callback."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:108
msgid "## Understanding applications"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:110
msgid "We have been working inside an application this entire time. Every time we changed a file and ran `mix compile`, we could see a `Generated kv app` message in the compilation output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:112
msgid "We can find the generated `.app` file at `_build/dev/lib/kv/ebin/kv.app`. Let's have a look at its contents:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:114
msgid ""
"```erlang\n"
"{application,kv,\n"
"             [{registered,[]},\n"
"              {description,\"kv\"},\n"
"              {applications,[kernel,stdlib,elixir,logger]},\n"
"              {vsn,\"0.0.1\"},\n"
"              {modules,['Elixir.KV','Elixir.KV.Bucket',\n"
"                        'Elixir.KV.Registry','Elixir.KV.Supervisor']}]}.\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:124
msgid "This file contains Erlang terms (written using Erlang syntax). Even though we are not familiar with Erlang, it is easy to guess this file holds our application definition. It contains our application `version`, all the modules defined by it, as well as a list of applications we depend on, like Erlang's `kernel`, `elixir` itself, and `logger` which is specified in the `:extra_applications` list in `mix.exs`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:126
msgid "It would be pretty boring to update this file manually every time we add a new module to our application. That's why Mix generates and maintains it for us."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:128
msgid "We can also configure the generated `.app` file by customizing the values returned by the `application/0` inside our `mix.exs` project file. We are going to do our first customization soon."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:130
msgid "### Starting applications"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:132
msgid "When we define a `.app` file, which is the application specification, we are able to start and stop the application as a whole. We haven't worried about this so far for two reasons:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:134
msgid "1. Mix automatically starts our current application for us"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:136
msgid "2. Even if Mix didn't start our application for us, our application does not yet do anything when it starts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:138
msgid "In any case, let's see how Mix starts the application for us. Let's start a project console with `iex -S mix` and try:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:140
msgid ""
"```iex\n"
"iex> Application.start(:kv)\n"
"{:error, {:already_started, :kv}}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:145
msgid "Oops, it's already started. Mix normally starts the whole hierarchy of applications defined in our project's `mix.exs` file and it does the same for all dependencies if they depend on other applications."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:147
msgid "We can pass an option to Mix to ask it to not start our application. Let's give it a try by running `iex -S mix run --no-start`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:149
msgid ""
"```iex\n"
"iex> Application.start(:kv)\n"
":ok\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:154
msgid "We can stop our `:kv` application as well as the `:logger` application, which is started by default with Elixir:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:156
msgid ""
"```iex\n"
"iex> Application.stop(:kv)\n"
":ok\n"
"iex> Application.stop(:logger)\n"
":ok\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:163
msgid "And let's try to start our application again:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:165
msgid ""
"```iex\n"
"iex> Application.start(:kv)\n"
"{:error, {:not_started, :logger}}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:170
msgid "Now we get an error because an application that `:kv` depends on (`:logger` in this case) isn't started. We need to either start each application manually in the correct order or call `Application.ensure_all_started` as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:172
msgid ""
"```iex\n"
"iex> Application.ensure_all_started(:kv)\n"
"{:ok, [:logger, :kv]}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:177
msgid "Nothing really exciting happens but it shows how we can control our application."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:179
msgid "> When you run `iex -S mix`, it is equivalent to running `iex -S mix run`. So whenever you need to pass more options to Mix when starting IEx, it's a matter of typing `iex -S mix run` and then passing any options the `run` command accepts. You can find more information about `run` by running `mix help run` in your shell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:181
msgid "### The application callback"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:183
msgid "Since we spent all this time talking about how applications are started and stopped, there must be a way to do something useful when the application starts. And indeed, there is!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:185
msgid "We can specify an application callback function. This is a function that will be invoked when the application starts. The function must return a result of `{:ok, pid}`, where `pid` is the process identifier of a supervisor process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:187
msgid "We can configure the application callback in two steps. First, open up the `mix.exs` file and change `def application` to the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:189
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"  def application do\n"
"    [\n"
"      extra_applications: [:logger],\n"
"      mod: {KV, []}\n"
"    ]\n"
"  end\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:198
msgid "The `:mod` option specifies the \"application callback module\", followed by the arguments to be passed on application start. The application callback module can be any module that implements the [Application](https://hexdocs.pm/elixir/Application.html) behaviour."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:200
msgid "Now that we have specified `KV` as the module callback, we need to change the `KV` module, defined in `lib/kv.ex`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:202
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"defmodule KV do\n"
"  use Application"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:206
msgid ""
"  def start(_type, _args) do\n"
"    KV.Supervisor.start_link(name: KV.Supervisor)\n"
"  end\n"
"end\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:212
msgid "When we `use Application`, we need to define a couple functions, similar to when we used `Supervisor` or `GenServer`. This time we only need to define a `start/2` function. If we wanted to specify custom behaviour on application stop, we could define a `stop/1` function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:214
msgid "Let's start our project console once again with `iex -S mix`. We will see a process named `KV.Registry` is already running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:216
msgid ""
"```iex\n"
"iex> KV.Registry.create(KV.Registry, \"shopping\")\n"
":ok\n"
"iex> KV.Registry.lookup(KV.Registry, \"shopping\")\n"
"{:ok, #PID<0.88.0>}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:223
msgid "How do we know this is working? After all, we are creating the bucket and then looking it up; of course it should work, right? Well, remember that `KV.Registry.create/2` uses `GenServer.cast/2`, and therefore will return `:ok` regardless of whether the message finds its target or not. At that point, we don't know whether the supervisor and the server are up, and if the bucket was created. However, `KV.Registry.lookup/2` uses `GenServer.call/3`, and will block and wait for a response from the server. We do get a positive response, so we know all is up and running."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:225
msgid "For an experiment, try reimplementing `KV.Registry.create/2` to use `GenServer.call/3` instead, and momentarily disable the application callback. Run the code above on the console again, and you will see the creation step fail straightaway."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:227
msgid "Don't forget to bring the code back to normal before resuming this tutorial!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:229
msgid "### Projects or applications?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:231
msgid "Mix makes a distinction between projects and applications. Based on the contents of our `mix.exs` file, we would say we have a Mix project that defines the `:kv` application. As we will see in later chapters, there are projects that don't define any application."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:233
msgid "When we say \"project\" you should think about Mix. Mix is the tool that manages your project. It knows how to compile your project, test your project and more. It also knows how to compile and start the application relevant to your project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:235
msgid "When we talk about applications, we talk about  <abbr title=\"Open Telecom Platform\">OTP</abbr>. Applications are the entities that are started and stopped as a whole by the runtime. You can learn more about applications in the [docs for the Application module](https://hexdocs.pm/elixir/Application.html), as well as by running `mix help compile.app` to learn more about the supported options in `def application`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:237
msgid "## Simple one for one supervisors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:239
msgid "We have now successfully defined our supervisor which is automatically started (and stopped) as part of our application lifecycle."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:241
msgid "Remember however that our `KV.Registry` is both linking (via `start_link`) and monitoring (via `monitor`) bucket processes in the `handle_cast/2` callback:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:243
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"{:ok, pid} = KV.Bucket.start_link([])\n"
"ref = Process.monitor(pid)\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:248
msgid "Links are bi-directional, which implies that a crash in a bucket will crash the registry. Although we now have the supervisor, which guarantees the registry will be back up and running, crashing the registry still means we lose all data associating bucket names to their respective processes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:250
msgid "In other words, we want the registry to keep on running even if a bucket crashes. Let's write a new registry test:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:252
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"test \"removes bucket on crash\", %{registry: registry} do\n"
"  KV.Registry.create(registry, \"shopping\")\n"
"  {:ok, bucket} = KV.Registry.lookup(registry, \"shopping\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:257
msgid ""
"  # Stop the bucket with non-normal reason\n"
"  Agent.stop(bucket, :shutdown)\n"
"  assert KV.Registry.lookup(registry, \"shopping\") == :error\n"
"end\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:263
msgid "The test is similar to \"removes bucket on exit\" except that we are being a bit more harsh by sending `:shutdown` as the exit reason instead of `:normal`. If a process terminates with a reason different than `:normal`, all linked processes receive an EXIT signal, causing the linked process to also terminate unless they are trapping exits."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:265
msgid "Since the bucket terminated, the registry went away with it, and our test fails when trying to `GenServer.call/3` it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:267
msgid ""
"```\n"
"  1) test removes bucket on crash (KV.RegistryTest)\n"
"     test/kv/registry_test.exs:26\n"
"     ** (exit) exited in: GenServer.call(#PID<0.148.0>, {:lookup, \"shopping\"}, 5000)\n"
"         ** (EXIT) no process: the process is not alive or there's no process currently associated with the given name, possibly because its application isn't started\n"
"     code: assert KV.Registry.lookup(registry, \"shopping\") == :error\n"
"     stacktrace:\n"
"       (elixir) lib/gen_server.ex:770: GenServer.call/3\n"
"       test/kv/registry_test.exs:33: (test)\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:278
msgid "We are going to solve this issue by defining a new supervisor that will spawn and supervise all buckets. There is one supervisor strategy, called `:simple_one_for_one`, that is the perfect fit for such situations: it allows us to specify a worker template and supervise many children based on this template. With this strategy, no workers are started during the supervisor initialization. Instead, a worker is started manually via the `Supervisor.start_child/2` function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:280
msgid "Let's define our `KV.BucketSupervisor` in `lib/kv/bucket_supervisor.ex` as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:282
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"defmodule KV.BucketSupervisor do\n"
"  use Supervisor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:286
msgid ""
"  # A simple module attribute that stores the supervisor name\n"
"  @name KV.BucketSupervisor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:289
msgid ""
"  def start_link(_opts) do\n"
"    Supervisor.start_link(__MODULE__, :ok, name: @name)\n"
"  end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:293
msgid ""
"  def start_bucket do\n"
"    Supervisor.start_child(@name, [])\n"
"  end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:297
msgid ""
"  def init(:ok) do\n"
"    Supervisor.init([KV.Bucket], strategy: :simple_one_for_one)\n"
"  end\n"
"end\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:303
msgid "There are two changes in this supervisor compared to the first one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:305
msgid "First of all, we have decided to give the supervisor a local name of `KV.BucketSupervisor`. While we could have passed the `opts` received on `start_link/1` to the supervisor, we chose to hard code the name for simplicity. Note this approach has downsides. For example, you wouldn't be able to start multiple instances of the `KV.BucketSupervisor` during tests, as they would conflict on the name. In this case, we will just allow all registries to use the same bucket supervisor at once, that won't be a problem since children of a simple one for one supervisor don't interfere with one another."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:307
msgid "We have also defined a `start_bucket/0` function that will start a bucket as a child of our supervisor named `KV.BucketSupervisor`. `start_bucket/0` is the function we are going to invoke instead of calling `KV.Bucket.start_link/1` directly in the registry."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:309
msgid "Run `iex -S mix` so we can give our new supervisor a try:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:311
msgid ""
"```iex\n"
"iex> {:ok, _} = KV.BucketSupervisor.start_link([])\n"
"{:ok, #PID<0.70.0>}\n"
"iex> {:ok, bucket} = KV.BucketSupervisor.start_bucket\n"
"{:ok, #PID<0.72.0>}\n"
"iex> KV.Bucket.put(bucket, \"eggs\", 3)\n"
":ok\n"
"iex> KV.Bucket.get(bucket, \"eggs\")\n"
"3\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:322
msgid "We are almost ready to use the simple one for one supervisor in our application. The first step is to change the registry to invoke `start_bucket`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:324
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"  def handle_cast({:create, name}, {names, refs}) do\n"
"    if Map.has_key?(names, name) do\n"
"      {:noreply, {names, refs}}\n"
"    else\n"
"      {:ok, pid} = KV.BucketSupervisor.start_bucket()\n"
"      ref = Process.monitor(pid)\n"
"      refs = Map.put(refs, ref, name)\n"
"      names = Map.put(names, name, pid)\n"
"      {:noreply, {names, refs}}\n"
"    end\n"
"  end\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:338
msgid "The second step is to make sure `KV.BucketSupervisor` is started when our application boots. We can do this by opening `lib/kv/supervisor.ex` and changing `init/1` to the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:340
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"  def init(:ok) do\n"
"    children = [\n"
"      {KV.Registry, name: KV.Registry},\n"
"      KV.BucketSupervisor\n"
"    ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:351
msgid "That's enough for our tests to pass but there is a resource leakage in our application. When a bucket terminates, the supervisor will start a new bucket in its place. After all, that's the role of the supervisor!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:353
msgid "However, when the supervisor restarts the new bucket, the registry does not know about it. So we will have an empty bucket in the supervisor that nobody can access! To solve this, we want to say that buckets are actually temporary. If they crash, regardless of the reason, they should not be restarted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:355
msgid "We can do this by passing the `restart: :temporary` option to `use Agent` in `KV.Bucket`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:357
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"defmodule KV.Bucket do\n"
"  use Agent, restart: :temporary\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:362
msgid "Let's also add a test to `test/kv/bucket_test.exs` that guarantees the bucket is temporary:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:364
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"  test \"are temporary workers\" do\n"
"    assert Supervisor.child_spec(KV.Bucket, []).restart == :temporary\n"
"  end\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:370
msgid "Our test uses the `Supervisor.child_spec/2` function to retrieve the child specification out of a module and then assert its restart value is `:temporary`. At this point, you may be wondering why use a supervisor if it never restarts its children. It happens that supervisors provide more than restarts, they are also responsible to guarantee proper startup and shutdown, especially in case of crashes in a supervision tree."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:372
msgid "## Supervision trees"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:374
msgid "When we added `KV.BucketSupervisor` as a child of `KV.Supervisor`, we began to have supervisors that supervise other supervisors, forming so-called \"supervision trees\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:376
msgid "Every time you add a new child to a supervisor, it is important to evaluate if the supervisor strategy is correct as well as the order of child processes. In this case, we are using `:one_for_one` and the `KV.Registry` is started before `KV.BucketSupervisor`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:378
msgid "One flaw that shows up right away is the ordering issue. Since `KV.Registry` invokes `KV.BucketSupervisor`, then the `KV.BucketSupervisor` must be started before `KV.Registry`. Otherwise it may happen that the registry attempts to reach the bucket supervisor before it has started."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:380
msgid "The second flaw is related to the supervision strategy. If `KV.Registry` dies, all information linking `KV.Bucket` names to bucket processes is lost. Therefore the `KV.BucketSupervisor` and all children must terminate too - otherwise we will have orphan processes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:382
msgid "In light of this observation, we should consider moving to another supervision strategy. The two other candidates are `:one_for_all` and `:rest_for_one`. A supervisor using the `:rest_for_one` will kill and restart child processes which were started *after* the crashed child. In this case, we would want `KV.BucketSupervisor` to terminate if `KV.Bucket` terminates. This would require the bucket supervisor to be placed after the registry. Which violates the ordering constraints we have established two paragraphs above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:384
msgid "So our last option is to go all in and pick the `:one_for_all` strategy: the supervisor will kill and restart all of its children processes whenever any one of them dies. This is a complete reasonable approach for our application, since the registry can't work without the bucket supervisor, and the bucket supervisor should terminate without the registry. Let's reimplement `init/1` in `KV.Supervisor` to encode those properties:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:386
msgid ""
"```elixir\n"
"  def init(:ok) do\n"
"    children = [\n"
"      KV.BucketSupervisor,\n"
"      {KV.Registry, name: KV.Registry}\n"
"    ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:393
msgid ""
"    Supervisor.init(children, strategy: :one_for_all)\n"
"  end\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:397
msgid "To help developers remember how to work with Supervisors and its convenience functions, [Benjamin Tan Wei Hao](http://benjamintan.io/) has created a [Supervisor cheat sheet](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/benjamintanweihao/elixir-cheatsheets/master/Supervisor_CheatSheet.pdf)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../getting-started/mix-otp/supervisor-and-application.markdown:399
msgid "There are two topics left before we move on to the next chapter."
msgstr ""

